WEBVTT

00:00:00.560 --> 00:00:03.920
<v Teacher>The word for <i>how</i> in Spanish is <b>cómo</b>.

00:00:03.920 --> 00:00:04.640
<v Student><b>Cómo</b>.

00:00:04.640 --> 00:00:10.160
<v Teacher><b>Cómo</b>. How do you think you would say <i>how are you?</i>, talking informally?

00:00:10.500 --> 00:00:11.540
<v Student>¿<b>Cómo estás</b>?

00:00:11.540 --> 00:00:17.220
<v Teacher>¿<b>Cómo estás</b>? Because when you ask somebody how they are, you're referring to their state.

00:00:17.220 --> 00:00:21.220
<v Teacher>¿<b>Cómo estás</b>? And formally, how would you ask?

00:00:22.000 --> 00:00:23.120
<v Student>¿<b>Cómo está</b>?

00:00:23.120 --> 00:00:26.960
<v Teacher>Good. And if you're asking more than one person?

00:00:26.960 --> 00:00:28.240
<v Student>¿<b>Cómo están</b>?

00:00:28.240 --> 00:00:32.400
<v Teacher>Very nice. The word for <i>where</i> is <b>dónde</b>.

00:00:32.400 --> 00:00:37.600
<v Teacher>So how would you say <i>where are you?</i>, talking informally?

00:00:37.600 --> 00:00:40.000
<v Student>¿<b>Dónde estás</b>?

00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:44.239
<v Teacher>¿<b>Dónde estás</b>? <i>I don't know where we are</i>. So what was <i>I don't know</i>?

00:00:47.580 --> 00:00:48.620
<v Student><b>No sé</b>.

00:00:48.620 --> 00:00:51.980
<v Teacher><b>No sé</b>. Good. <i>I don't know where we are</i>:

00:00:51.980 --> 00:00:55.340
<v Student><b>No sé donde estamos</b>.

00:00:55.340 --> 00:00:59.180
<v Teacher>Good. <b>No sé dónde estamos</b>. Good.

00:00:59.180 --> 00:01:01.420
<v Teacher>How would you say <i>I am here</i>?

00:01:01.420 --> 00:01:03.739
<v Student><b>Estoy aquí</b>.

00:01:03.739 --> 00:01:10.060
<v Teacher><b>Estoy aquí</b>, <b>estoy acá</b>. How would you say <i>I want to be here</i>?

00:01:10.680 --> 00:01:13.240
<v Student><b>Quiero estar aquí</b>.

00:01:13.240 --> 00:01:17.720
<v Teacher>Good. <b>Quiero estar aquí</b>. Good.

00:01:17.720 --> 00:01:20.920
<v Teacher>How would you say <i>I'm going to be here later</i>?

00:01:20.920 --> 00:01:23.000
<v Teacher>What was the word for <i>late</i>?

00:01:23.000 --> 00:01:24.600
<v Student><b>Tarde</b>.

00:01:24.600 --> 00:01:26.759
<v Teacher><b>Tarde</b>. Good. And <i>later</i> or <i>more late</i>?

00:01:26.759 --> 00:01:27.640
<v Student><b>Más tarde</b>.

00:01:27.640 --> 00:01:31.000
<v Teacher>Good. So <i>I'm going to be here later</i>:

00:01:31.000 --> 00:01:35.380
<v Student><b>Voy a estar aquí más tarde</b>.

00:01:35.380 --> 00:01:40.100
<v Teacher>Good. <b>Voy a estar aquí más tarde</b>.

00:01:40.100 --> 00:01:45.300
<v Teacher><b>Voy</b> is <i>I go</i> or <i>I'm going</i>. How do you say <i>you go</i> or <i>you are going</i>, speaking informally?

00:01:46.280 --> 00:01:47.080
<v Student><b>Vas</b>.

00:01:47.080 --> 00:01:52.120
<v Teacher><b>Vas</b>. Good. So how would you say <i>where are you going to be</i>?

00:01:52.120 --> 00:01:56.040
<v Teacher>So break it up: <i>where are you going to be</i>?:

00:01:57.180 --> 00:02:00.140
<v Student>¿<b>Dónde vas a estar</b>?

00:02:00.140 --> 00:02:04.860
<v Teacher>Yes. ¿<b>Dónde vas a estar</b>? <i>Where are you going to be</i>? Good.

00:02:04.860 --> 00:02:09.900
<v Teacher>So let's run through the forms again, and let's use the words for emphasis just to practice them.

00:02:09.900 --> 00:02:14.300
<v Teacher>So <i>I am</i> is:

00:02:14.300 --> 00:02:14.700
<v Student><b>Yo estoy</b>.

00:02:14.700 --> 00:02:16.220
<v Teacher>Good. <b>Yo estoy</b>. <i>He is</i>:

00:02:18.140 --> 00:02:19.580
<v Student><b>Él está</b>.

00:02:19.580 --> 00:02:21.020
<v Teacher>Good. <b>Él está</b>.

00:02:21.020 --> 00:02:22.940
<v Teacher><i>She is</i>:

00:02:22.940 --> 00:02:24.380
<v Student><b>Ella está</b>.

00:02:24.380 --> 00:02:27.980
<v Teacher>Good. And <i>you</i> (talking formally) <i>are</i>:

00:02:29.240 --> 00:02:30.920
<v Student><b>Usted está</b>.

00:02:30.920 --> 00:02:32.760
<v Teacher><b>Usted está</b>. Good.

00:02:32.760 --> 00:02:36.440
<v Teacher><i>They are</i>, using the word for <i>they</i>:

00:02:36.440 --> 00:02:37.720
<v Student><b>Ellos están</b>.

00:02:37.720 --> 00:02:38.840
<v Teacher><b>Ellos están</b>. Or for feminine:

00:02:40.879 --> 00:02:42.239
<v Student><b>Ellas están</b>.

00:02:42.239 --> 00:02:45.040
<v Teacher>Good. What is <i>we are</i>?

00:02:45.040 --> 00:02:46.480
<v Student><b>Nosotros estamos</b>.

00:02:46.480 --> 00:02:48.799
<v Teacher>Good. And for feminine?

00:02:48.799 --> 00:02:52.740
<v Student><b>Nosotros</b>, <b>nosotras estamos</b>.

00:02:52.740 --> 00:02:56.660
<v Teacher>Good. So <b>nosotros</b> changes to <b>nosotras</b>.

00:02:56.660 --> 00:03:00.340
<v Teacher><i>You are</i>, talking informally:

00:03:01.560 --> 00:03:02.280
<v Student><b>Estás</b>.

00:03:02.280 --> 00:03:06.840
<v Teacher>Good. And if we used the word for <i>you</i>:

00:03:06.840 --> 00:03:07.400
<v Student><b>Tú estás</b>.

00:03:07.400 --> 00:03:10.360
<v Teacher>Good. <b>Tú estás</b>. <b>Tú estás</b>. Good.

00:03:10.360 --> 00:03:17.819
<v Teacher>How would you ask more than one person, <i>where do you have to be later</i>?

00:03:17.819 --> 00:03:19.500
<v Teacher>So the first bit is <i>where</i>.

00:03:19.500 --> 00:03:21.959
<v Student><b>Dónde</b>.

00:03:21.959 --> 00:03:26.760
<v Teacher><i>Do you have?</i>, and we are talking to <i>you</i> (plural), which is the same as <i>they</i>.

00:03:26.760 --> 00:03:28.879
<v Teacher><i>Do you have</i>? Yeah, what's <i>to have</i>?

00:03:28.879 --> 00:03:30.640
<v Student><b>Tener</b>.

00:03:30.640 --> 00:03:40.239
<v Teacher><b>Tener</b>. Good. And we have it as <i>-tain</i> in words like <i>maintain</i>-<b>mantener</b>, <i>contain</i>-<b>contener</b>,

00:03:40.239 --> 00:03:46.340
<v Teacher><i>sustain</i>-<b>sostener</b>, <i>entertain</i>-<b>entretener</b>, <i>obtain</i>-<b>obtener</b>.

00:03:46.340 --> 00:03:51.780
<v Teacher>That will help us. So first we want to build <i>you guys have</i> from <b>tener</b>.

00:03:51.780 --> 00:03:53.800
<v Student><b>Tienen</b>.

00:03:53.800 --> 00:03:59.879
<v Teacher>Good. So <i>where do you have to be later</i>, to <i>you</i> (plural). Try it.

00:04:01.920 --> 00:04:05.920
<v Student><b>Dónde tienen están</b>.

00:04:05.920 --> 00:04:07.360
<v Teacher>Slower.

00:04:07.360 --> 00:04:12.560
<v Student>Oh sorry, <i>to be</i>, it's in the, yes. <b>Dónde</b>, and I've forgotten the other one now.

00:04:12.560 --> 00:04:15.220
<v Teacher>It's okay, work it out again.

00:04:15.220 --> 00:04:17.940
<v Student><b>Dónde tienen estar</b>.

00:04:18.019 --> 00:04:24.980
<v Teacher>There is something we need to add to <b>tienen</b> to get this meaning of <i>have to</i>, and it's not a comfortable translation.

00:04:24.980 --> 00:04:30.080
<v Student><b>Dónde tienen que estar</b>...

00:04:30.080 --> 00:04:31.120
<v Teacher><i>Later</i>:

00:04:31.120 --> 00:04:32.000
<v Student><b>Más tarde</b>.

00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:34.960
<v Teacher>¿<b>Dónde tienen que estar más tarde</b>? Good.

00:04:34.960 --> 00:04:41.720
<v Teacher>You might want to say <i>he must be here</i>, and you can use this in the same way as you do in English, to refer to probability.

00:04:41.720 --> 00:04:46.200
<v Teacher>"Oh he must be here by now", or something like this. You have the same use in Spanish.

00:04:46.200 --> 00:04:50.460
<v Teacher>And <i>must</i> is the same as <i>to owe</i>, which is related to <i>debt</i>.

00:04:50.460 --> 00:04:52.620
<v Teacher>So what was <i>to owe</i>?

00:04:52.620 --> 00:04:53.419
<v Student><b>Deber</b>.

00:04:53.419 --> 00:04:54.379
<v Teacher><b>Deber</b>. Good.

00:04:54.379 --> 00:04:56.379
<v Teacher>So <i>he owes</i> or <i>he must</i>:

00:04:57.240 --> 00:04:58.120
<v Student><b>Debe</b>.

00:04:58.120 --> 00:05:01.400
<v Teacher><b>Debe</b>. This <i>e</i> doesn't split. Good. <b>Debe</b>.

00:05:01.400 --> 00:05:04.840
<v Teacher>So <i>he must be here</i>:

00:05:04.840 --> 00:05:07.400
<v Student><b>Debe estar aquí</b>.

00:05:07.400 --> 00:05:09.880
<v Teacher>Good. And <i>he must be tired</i>:

00:05:10.420 --> 00:05:13.380
<v Student><b>Debe estar cansado</b>.

00:05:13.380 --> 00:05:15.620
<v Teacher>Good. <b>Debe estar cansado</b>.

00:05:15.620 --> 00:05:17.700
<v Teacher><i>They must be tired</i>:

00:05:17.700 --> 00:05:21.500
<v Student><b>Deben estar cansados</b>.

00:05:21.500 --> 00:05:24.860
<v Teacher>Very good. What if they were females?

00:05:24.860 --> 00:05:26.220
<v Student><b>Cansadas</b>.

00:05:26.220 --> 00:05:28.940
<v Teacher>All together. Don't miss the fun.

00:05:28.940 --> 00:05:33.280
<v Student><b>Deben estar cansadas</b>.

00:05:33.280 --> 00:05:36.240
<v Teacher>Good. <b>Deben estar cansadas</b>.

00:05:36.240 --> 00:05:38.800
<v Teacher><i>To remain</i> was <b>quedar</b>. <b>Quedar</b>.

00:05:38.800 --> 00:05:40.720
<v Student><b>Quedar</b>.

00:05:40.720 --> 00:05:46.160
<v Teacher>And to get the meaning of <i>I stay</i>, we say <i>I remain myself</i>.

00:05:46.160 --> 00:05:48.960
<v Teacher>So how would that sound? <i>I remain myself</i>:

00:05:51.080 --> 00:05:52.039
<v Student><b>Me quedo</b>.

00:05:52.039 --> 00:05:54.440
<v Teacher><b>Me quedo</b>. <i>I am staying</i>.

00:05:54.440 --> 00:05:58.919
<v Teacher>How would <i>we are staying</i>, or <i>we remain ourselves</i>, be?

00:05:59.699 --> 00:06:01.060
<v Student><b>Nos quedamos</b>.

00:06:01.060 --> 00:06:10.560
<v Teacher>Good. <i>We are not going to stay, because we are very tired</i>. <i>We are not going to stay, because we are very tired</i>.

00:06:10.560 --> 00:06:17.199
<v Teacher>So the first bit that needs to command all of our attention is <i>we are not going</i>:

00:06:18.199 --> 00:06:19.240
<v Student><b>No vamos</b>.

00:06:19.240 --> 00:06:25.080
<v Teacher><b>No vamos</b>. <i>We are not going to stay</i>, so <i>we are not going to remain ourselves</i>:

00:06:25.680 --> 00:06:29.200
<v Student><b>No vamos a quedarnos</b>.

00:06:29.200 --> 00:06:37.680
<v Teacher>Good. <b>No vamos a quedarnos</b> or <b>no nos vamos a quedar</b>. You can have this as well. <b>No nos vamos a quedar</b>.

00:06:37.680 --> 00:06:41.020
<v Teacher><i>Because</i>, same as <i>why</i>:

00:06:41.020 --> 00:06:41.900
<v Student><b>Porque</b>.

00:06:41.900 --> 00:06:48.860
<v Teacher><b>Porque</b>. <i>We are very tired</i>. And let's be a masculine or a mixed group. <i>We are very tired</i>:

00:06:48.860 --> 00:06:53.320
<v Student><b>Estamos muy cansados</b>.

00:06:53.320 --> 00:06:56.360
<v Teacher>Good. Now all together and not from memory.

00:06:56.360 --> 00:07:03.800
<v Teacher>Thinking about it again, block by block. If you rush it, you will trip, and tripping is very time-consuming.

00:07:03.800 --> 00:07:09.500
<v Teacher>So, <i>we are not going to remain ourselves</i>. <i>To stay</i>:

00:07:09.500 --> 00:07:12.460
<v Student><b>No vamos a quedarnos</b>.

00:07:12.460 --> 00:07:15.740
<v Teacher>Good. <i>Because we are very tired</i>:

00:07:15.740 --> 00:07:20.060
<v Student><b>Porque estamos muy cansados</b>.

00:07:20.060 --> 00:07:21.340
<v Teacher>Well done.

00:07:21.340 --> 00:07:25.340
<v Teacher><b>No vamos a quedarnos</b>, <b>no nos vamos a quedar</b> <b>porque</b>, <b>estamos muy cansados</b>.

00:07:25.340 --> 00:07:29.900
<v Teacher>Very good.

